    "answer": null,
    "explanation": "<p>To confirm the presence of the cloned DNA fragment in the plasmid, we consider the digestion by different restriction enzymes:</p>\n\n<p><strong>Case (a): Digestion with Not I and EcoRI.</strong>  </p>\n\n\n<p><p>The recombinant plasmid contains three Not I sites due to the insert and one EcoRI site. </p></p>\n<p><p>This digestion results in four DNA fragments:</p>\n\n<p><p>1900 base pairs</p></p>\n<p><p>1700 base pairs</p></p>\n<p><p>500 base pairs</p></p>\n<p><p>400 base pairs</p></p></p>\n\n\n<p><strong>Case (b): Digestion with Not I and Hind III.</strong>  </p>\n\n\n<p><p>In this scenario, the plasmid is cut at the three Not I sites and one Hind III site.</p></p>\n<p><p>This digestion also yields four fragments, but of different sizes:</p>\n\n<p><p>1900 base pairs</p></p>\n<p><p>1100 base pairs</p></p>\n<p><p>900 base pairs</p></p>\n<p><p>600 base pairs</p></p></p>\n\n<p>By analyzing the gel electrophoresis pattern for each case, these fragment sizes help confirm the presence and length of the inserted DNA in the plasmid.</p>",
