    "comprehension": null,
    "direction": null,
    "content": "As opposed to DNA replication within the cell, discontinuous synthesis of DNA does NOT occur in a polymerase chain reaction (PCR). Why?\n",
    "options": [
      {
        "identifier": "A",
        "content": "The replication fork is formed and DNA ligase activity of the Taq polymerase joins the discontinuous fragments.\n"
      },
      {
        "identifier": "B",
        "content": "The replication fork is formed and Taq polymerase extends DNA in both $3^{\\prime}$ to $5^{\\prime}$ and $5^{\\prime}$ to $3^{\\prime}$ direction.\n"
      },
      {
        "identifier": "C",
        "content": "Denaturation step in PCR substitutes for the replication fork and Taq polymerase extends DNA only in the $3^{\\prime}$ to $5^{\\prime}$ direction.\n"
      },
      {
        "identifier": "D",
        "content": "Denaturation step in PCR substitutes for the replication fork and Taq polymerase extends DNA only in the $5^{\\prime}$ to $3^{\\prime}$ direction."
      }
    ],
    "correct_options": [
      "D"
    ],
    "answer": null,
    "explanation": "<p>In PCR, the denaturation step separates the double-stranded DNA into single strands. The Taq polymerase then extends the DNA in the $5^{\\prime}$ to $3^{\\prime}$ direction. PCR does not involve the formation of Okazaki fragments or discontinuous synthesis because it operates on single-stranded templates, and the extension is continuous on each strand.</p>",
